      <h1 class="heading-xlarge">Get started</h1>

      <h2 class="heading-large">Check GOV.UK Verify is right for your service</h2>
      <h2 class="heading-medium">GOV.UK Verify could be right for your service if it needs to:</h2>
      <ul class="list list-bullet">
        <li>have legal confirmation that a user is who they say they are, for example if they’re signing a mortgage deed</li>
        <li>show a user’s personal information to them, like their driving licence or passport details</li>
        <li>pay money to a user</li>
        <li>give the user something valuable, like a <a href="https://www.gov.uk/blue-badge-scheme-information-council">Blue Badge</a> or a council house</li>
      </ul>
      <p>You might not need GOV.UK Verify if you only need to recognise a returning user. For example, if you’re making an appeal to the tax tribunal you can <a href="https://appeal-tax-tribunal.service.gov.uk/">save your appeal and return to it later</a>  by creating an account.</p>
      <h2 class="heading-medium">To help you decide if GOV.UK Verify is right for your service, you should think about:</h2>
      <ul class="list list-bullet">
        <li>what your service lets users do</li>
        <li>whether you need to know the identity of your users, or whether knowing they are the same person every time will be enough</li>
        <li>whether you need to be able to take users to court if they’ve been fraudulent</li>
        <li>whether any other controls are in place to prevent fraud</li>
      </ul>
      <h2 class="heading-medium">Organisations that can use GOV.UK Verify include:</h2>
      <ul class="list list-bullet">
        <li>central government</li>
        <li>local government</li>
        <li>NHS</li>
        <li>police</li>
      </ul>
